Introduction¶

Data Set¶

FBI Gun Data

Overview and Notes¶

The data comes from the FBI's National Instant Criminal Background Check System (NICS). The NICS is used by to determine whether a prospective buyer is eligible to buy firearms or explosives. Gun shops call into this system to ensure that each customer does not have a criminal record or isn’t otherwise ineligible to make a purchase. The data has been supplemented with state level data from census.gov.

The NICS data is found in one sheet of an .xlsx file. It contains the number of firearm checks by month, state, and type. The U.S. census data is found in a .csv file. It contains several variables at the state level. Most variables just have one data point per state (2016), but a few have data for more than one year.

Function to export data frame with name as time-date in both xlsx and csv formate

In [168]:
# Function to export data frame with name as time-date in both xlsx and csv formate
def export_df(df):
   now = datetime.now() # current date and time
   date_time = now.strftime("%Y_%m_%d-%H_%M_%S")
   excel_file_name =  date_time + '.xlsx' 
   csv_file_name =  date_time + '.csv'
   print  (excel_file_name)
   print  (csv_file_name) 
   df.to_excel(excel_file_name)
   df.to_csv(csv_file_name)

Relationship between increase in population growth and increase in Gun Permits¶

Rescaling Population to show trend inrelevat to the scale of Gun_Permits_Totals

In [176]:
# Relationship between increase in population growth and increase in Gun Permits

y  = final_df['US_State']
x1 = final_df['Gun_Permits_Totals']
x2 = final_df['States_Population_2016']
x3 = final_df['States_Population_2010']
# Rescaling Population to show trend inrelevat to the scale of Gun_Permits_Totals
x2/=1000
x3/=1000
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20, 40))
ax = fig.add_axes([0,0,1,1])
l1 = ax.plot(x1,y,'y-') # solid line with yellow colour and square marker
l2 = ax.plot(x2,y,'g-') # dash line with green colour and circle marker
l3 = ax.plot(x3,y,'b-') # solid line with yellow colour and square marker
ax.legend(labels = ('Gun_Permits_Totals', 'States_Population_2016', 'States_Population_2010'), loc = 'upper right') # legend placed at lower right
ax.set_title('Relationship between increase in population growth and increase in Gun Permits')
ax.set_xlabel('Totals')
ax.set_ylabel('state')

Conclusions¶

Although Kentucky state has the highest Gun Permits (Gun_Permits_Totals) and Calfornia state has the heighest populations (States_Population_2016 & States_Population_2010)

But the overall picture illustrate that the Gun permits corelate to population
